<br> <br>
&#226;&#166;and they happily flag non-malicious content as malicious regardless of how you try to protect it from their all-seeing eye. I&#226;(TM)ve even had security incident reports drafted for GDPR reporting purposes be flagged as malware, finding out from Microsoft it was literally because they contained *images* containing the phishing URLs (in a non-clickable form) of the already taken down phishing sites in them. When that happens, you have to mess about because email, OneDrive, SharePoint, Teams and every other usual method will not let you send the report to their intended recipients. To add insult to injury, these URLs were not blocked by Microsoft while the attacks took place and also bear in mind you have 72 hours to produce reports when incidents occur, regardless of whether the UK ICO decides they care or not.
<br> <br>
I think it is safe to say that Microsoft analyses everything they can already with or without people&#226;(TM)s consent and will totally make use of LLMs even if you ignore this Copilot feature.</div>
